Objective
Detect PowerShell executions that use encoded commands, a common obfuscation technique used by malware and post-exploitation frameworks.

Data Source

  -Sysmon Operational Logs

  -Event ID 1 (Process Creation)

Why This Matters
Attackers frequently abuse PowerShell’s -EncodedCommand flag to hide malicious intent, bypass basic logging, and evade signature-based detections. This behavior is strongly associated with real-world malware, ransomware, and living-off-the-land attacks.

Detection Logic Summary
This detection identifies:

  -PowerShell or PowerShell Core (powershell.exe / pwsh.exe)

  -Process creation events

  -Use of encoded command flags (-enc, -EncodedCommand)

  -Full command-line visibility via Sysmon telemetry

Detection Logic:

  index=sysmon
| rex field=_raw "<EventID(?:[^>]*)>(?<EventID>\d+)</EventID>"
| search EventID=1
| rex field=_raw "(?i)<Data Name=['\"]Image['\"]>(?<Image>[^<]+)</Data>"
| rex field=_raw "(?i)<Data Name=['\"]CommandLine['\"]>(?<CommandLine>[^<]+)</Data>"
| search Image="*\\powershell.exe" OR Image="*\\pwsh.exe"
| regex CommandLine="(?i)\s-(enc|encodedcommand)\b"
| table _time host Image CommandLine
| sort - _time


Validation

-Detection was validated by executing both benign and encoded PowerShell commands on the Windows endpoint

-Encoded commands successfully triggered Sysmon Event ID 1 and were indexed into Splunk

-Results were confirmed using Verbose search mode to ensure full field extraction
